03763nmm a2200493Ia 9780520917163DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20231994cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209171637 a10.1525/97805209171632doi  a(DE-B1597)543068  a(OCoLC)1149475922  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aE169.12b.J35 1995eb 7aHIS0360002bisacsh04a973.922201 aJamison, Andrew, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSeeds of the Sixties /cAndrew Jamison, Ron Eyerman.  aReprint 2019 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2023] 4c©1994  a1 online resource (248 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a"The Sixties." The powerful images conveyed by those two words have become an enduring part of American cultural and political history. But where did Sixties radicalism come from? Who planted the intellectual seeds that brought it into being? These questions are answered with striking clarity in Andrew Jamison and Ron Eyerman's book. The result is a combination of history and biography that vividly portrays an entire culture in transition.The authors focus on specific individuals, each of whom in his or her distinctive way carried the ideas of the 1930s into the decades after World War II, and each of whom shared in inventing a new kind of intellectual partisanship. They begin with C. Wright Mills, Hannah Arendt, and Erich Fromm and show how their work linked the "old left" of the Thirties to the "new left" of the Sixties. Lewis Mumford, Rachel Carson, and Fairfield Osborn laid the groundwork for environmental activism; Herbert Marcuse, Margaret Mead, and Leo Szilard articulated opposition to the postwar "scientific-technological state." Alternatives to mass culture were proposed by Allen Ginsberg, James Baldwin, and Mary McCarthy; and Saul Alinsky, Dorothy Day, and Martin Luther King, Jr., made politics personal.This is an unusual book, written with an intimacy that brings to life both intellect and emotion. The portraits featured here clearly demonstrate that the transforming radicalism of the Sixties grew from the legacy of an earlier generation of thinkers. With a deep awareness of the historical trends in American culture, the authors show us the continuing relevance these partisan intellectuals have for our own age."In a time colored by 'political correctness' and the ascendancy of market liberalism, it is well to remember the partisan intellectuals of the 1950s. They took sides and dissented without becoming dogmatic. May we be able to say the same about ourselves."—from Chapter 7  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh1 aEyerman, Ron, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520917163?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520917163423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520917163/original  aEBA_EMB  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles